Title: Which Poem is Better?
Description: Read two poems and rate them
Input.Title: PANCAKE? (Where the Sidewalk Ends)
Input.Poem:
Who wants a pancake,

Sweet and piping hot?

Good little Grace looks up and says,

“I’ll take the one on top.”

Who else wants a pancake,

Fresh off the griddle?

Terrible Theresa smiles and says,

“I’ll take the one in the middle.”
Input.first_line: Who wants a pancake,
Input.line2: With syrup like lake,
Input.line3: Poured in the middle.
Input.line4: The pancake went flat.
Input.line5: The griddle was broken.
Input.line6: The syrup is swet.
Input.line7: Breakfast has spoken.
Answer.reason: The first poem told a story and had a good flow.  In the second poem, I liked the first paragraph, but the second paragraph went off the rails and made no sense to me.  The pancake went flat - what is that? The griddle was broken . . . wait, what? The pancake was already cooked!  The last sentence is breakfast has spoken . . but I just can't figure out what breakfast said when it spoke!

Title: Which Poem is Better?
Description: Read two poems and rate them
Input.Title: MY RULES (Where the Sidewalk Ends)
Input.Poem:
If you want to marry me, here’s what you’ll have to do:

You must learn how to make a perfect chicken-dumpling stew.

And you must sew my holey socks,

And soothe my troubled mind,

And develop the knack for scratching my back,

And keep my shoes spotlessly shined.

And while I rest you must rake up the leaves,

And when it’s hailing and snowing

You must shovel the walk… and be still when I talk,

And—hey—where are you going?

Input.line5: Rules be damned
Input.line6: Your mother is a troubled cow!
Input.line7: Oh, she'll love me yes ma'am!
